  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best online resources for learning how to build Android applications?",
  "response": "There are many excellent online resources for learning how to build Android applications. Here are some of the best ones:\n\n1. **Udacity**:\n   - **Android Basics Nanodegree by Google**: This program is designed for beginners with no prior programming experience.\n   - **Android Developer Nanodegree**: For more advanced learners, this program offers deeper insights into Android app development.\n\n2. **Coursera**:\n   - **Android App Development for Beginners**: This course covers the basics of Android app development.\n   - **Advanced Android Development**: After mastering the basics, this course takes you through more complex aspects of Android development.\n\n3. **Google Developers Training**:\n   - **Android Developer Fundamentals**: Google offers free courses and tutorials on Android development, including videos, sample code, and documentation.\n   - **Android Kotlin Fundamentals**: Focused on Kotlin, which is now the preferred language for Android development.\n\n4. **Udemy**:\n   - **The Complete Android Developer Course**: A comprehensive course that covers everything from basic to advanced topics in Android development.\n   - **Android App Development Bootcamp**: Another thorough course that includes practical projects and exercises.\n\n5. **YouTube**:\n   - **Coding with Mitch**: Mitch offers a variety of tutorials on Android development.\n   - **Android Developers Channel**: The official channel by Google provides talks, tutorials, and updates on Android development.\n\n6. **FreeCodeCamp**:\n   - FreeCodeCamp offers articles, tutorials, and videos on Android development, often focusing on practical, hands-on learning.\n\n7. **Pluralsight**:\n   - Offers a variety of Android development courses, from beginner to advanced levels, with assessments to track your progress.\n\n8. **LinkedIn Learning**:\n   - Provides numerous courses on Android development, covering both Java and Kotlin.\n\n9. **Stack Overflow & Reddit**:\n   - These forums can be invaluable for troubleshooting, advice, and community support.\n\n10. **Official Documentation**:\n    - **Android Developers**: Google's official documentation is a must-read. It includes guides, API references, and best practices.\n\n11. **Books**:\n    - **\"Android Programming: The Big Nerd Ranch Guide\"**: Highly regarded in the developer community.\n    - **\"Head First Android Development\"**: A beginner-friendly book that uses a visual approach to teaching.\n\nThese resources provide a mix of theoretical knowledge and practical experience, allowing you to learn at your own pace and gradually build up your skills in Android app development.",
